In many previous floods both NB and SB lanes of 169 were covered with water. Traffic was rerouted to county roads west of 169. The recent projects allows vehicles to stay on 169 and all but the most extreme floods. Although some lane closures can be expected.

The entire length of 169 was not lifted up 8 1/2 feet. 8 1/2 feet was the largest grade raise that was completed in the same area where NB and SB traffic will be sharing to make sure the southbound lanes would be not impacted by floodwaters as they were back in the 2014 flood.

This traffic change will look much like a normal construction project that driver have experienced over the last few years. In fact, it is using a crossover that was built as a part of the project last summer especially for this purpose. Both NB & SB Traffic’s will use SB lanes

The projects to raise Hwy 169 in recent years were intended to keep traffic moving on 169 during most floods. The northbound section beginning a little more than a mile north of St Peter would have been prohibitively expensive to raise high enough to allow for four-lane travel.

The best way to prepare your vehicle for winter weather: Make sure your lights are working along with your wipers. Remove the snow and ice from your windows. "That's a risk to everyone," @MSPPIO Lt. Shank says. Don't drive on bald tires. Top off your fluids.

Attention parents of teenage drivers: The best way to get them used to driving in winter weather is practice, @MSPPIO Lt. Shank says. Take them to an empty lot so they can get comfortable. #WinterDrivingReminders @MPRnews @AngelaDavisMPR

MnDOT's Feb 1975 newsletter ran this photo: "On Jan 13, following the 'storm of the century,' this photo was taken of the southbound lane of I-35 south of TH 14 at Owatonna. The freeway was impassable at this point before a [MnDOT] snowplow cleared out the gigantic snowdrift." pic.twitter.com/m7tcSpq5kJ
